observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor undertake the following courses of action:
Formulate and observe internal rules and procedures on the proper monitoring and accountability of transaction documents to ensure a systematic and timely submission of documents to appropriate Offices;
Require the Municipal Accountant to support the identified reconciling items by submitting to the Office of the Auditor the required disbursement vouchers and its supporting documents under the General Fund, and identify the details and nature of transactions under the Trust Fund and Special Education Fund;
Advise the Municipal Accountant to provide a copy of the August 2017 and December 2018 subsidiary ledgers of Cash in Bank account to further verify the debit memo adjustments and justify the adjusting entries made to correct the CYs 2017 and 2018 errors, otherwise, reverse the entries and restate the affected accounts;
Require the Municipal Accountant to carefully review all the reconciling items in the Bank Reconciliation Statements and ensure that these items are appropriately and promptly adjusted in the books, which are duly supported with valid documents, and/or take other necessary procedures in addressing the bank and book reconciling items of the Cash-in-Bank account; and
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to ensure timely submission of the disbursement vouchers and its supporting documents to the Accounting Department once checks are released to the payees, for the timely recording in the books of accounts of the LGU and ensure a reliable Accounts Payable account.

We recommended that the Management undertake the following:
Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare necessary adjusting entries to revert the entries made to the Other Receivables account totaling P72,760.95, since these are not properly supported with the required documents in compliance with COA Circular 2012-001 dated 
June 14, 2012;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to conduct regular and periodic verification, analysis, and validation of receivables to ensure its accuracy and existence;
For dormant accounts where records and documents are no longer available, the Head of the Agency shall create an Investigation Committee to determine the cause/s of loss or destruction of documents, identify the officials and employees liable for such loss, and look into the absence or presence of negligence on the part of the Accountable Officer; and
Initiate the request for authority to write-off the dormant Other Receivables account, and comply with guidelines and procedures on the proper disposition and write-off/derecognition of dormant accounts outlined in COA Circular No. 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023.

Expenditures amounting to P1,344,037.98 that were charged against the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund (LDRRMF) were not related to prescribed disaster risk management expenses, contrary to Section 5.0 of NDRRMC-DBM-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular (JMC) No. 2013-1 dated March 25, 2013, thereby rendering the transactions irregular and defeating the purpose for which the Fund was created.

We have recommended that the Management submit justification as to why the total amount of P1,344,037.98 should not be disallowed in audit. Further, we have recommended that the Management utilize solely the LDRRM Fund to implement projects and activities under the legislated thematic areas, namely: 1) disaster prevention and mitigation; 
2) disaster preparedness; 
3) disaster response; and 4) disaster rehabilitation and recovery, as provided in Section 21 of RA 10121 and Section 5.0 of NDRRMC-DBM-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular (JMC) No. 2013-1 dated March 25, 2013.

We have recommended that the Management:

a.	Submit a revised Inventory Report using the prescribed form of Report of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment showing relevant information, such as property number, unit value, balance of PPE per property cards and per count;

b.	Update the property records based on the results of physical inventory, and reconcile the same with accounting records to make the records reflective of the actual count of PPEs;

c.	Undertake all other procedures prescribed under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts in the financial statements; and 

d.	Direct the Municipal Accountant and GSO to prepare the PPE ledger cards and Property Cards, respectively, for each item of the PPE pursuant to Section 114, Paragraph 4 of the MNGAs for LGUs, Volume I.

We recommended Management the following:

Create the Inventory Committee composed of adequate number of members to conduct physical inventory of all PPEs of the Municipality within the period prescribed under the aforementioned COA Circular;

Thru the Inventory Committee created, update the property records based on the results of physical inventory, and reconcile with accounting records;

Undertake all other procedures prescribed under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts in the financial statements; and 

After the inventory taking, direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the updated ledger cards for each item of the PPE pursuant to the Section 269 of the GAM for LGUs.

We recommended that the Management:
Submit a revised Inventory Report using the prescribed form of Report of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment showing relevant information, such as property number, unit value, balance of PPE per property cards and per count;
Update the property records based on the results of physical inventory, and reconcile the same with accounting records to make the records reflective of the actual count of PPEs;
Undertake all other procedures prescribed under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts in the financial statements; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant and GSO to prepare the PPE ledger cards and Property Cards, respectively, for each item of the PPE pursuant to Section 114, Paragraph 4 of the MNGAs for LGUs, Volume I.

We recommended Management the following:
Create the Inventory Committee composed of adequate number of members to conduct physical inventory of all PPEs of the Municipality within the period prescribed under the aforementioned COA Circular;
Thru the Inventory Committee created, update the property records based on the results of physical inventory, and reconcile with accounting records;
Undertake all other procedures prescribed under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts in the financial statements; and
After the inventory taking, direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the updated ledger cards for each item of the PPE pursuant to the Section 269 of the GAM for LGUs.
The management committed to conduct inventory of all PPEs in accordance with the procedures prescribed under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Require, by sending demand letters, all concerned officials and employees to liquidate immediately their outstanding cash advances. Refrain from granting additional cash advances to those who still have unliquidated balances, and observe strictly the rules and regulations on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances.

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to closely monitor the outstanding cash advances and issue demand letters for the immediate liquidation or settlement of the same. Enforce sanctions under COA Circular No. 97-002, where necessary;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all disbursement vouchers on the grant of cash advances for Salaries, Wages, Honoraria and Other similar payments should be supported by approved payroll and the amount to be granted should be based on the net amount of the payroll;

Effect refund of cash advance through salary deductions as provided under Item 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002, where necessary, to avoid sanctions provided by law.

Avoid the grant of cash advance to Officials and Employees who are not cashiers, disbursing officers, paymasters, and/or property/supply officers or designated disbursing officers except for their travelling expenditures.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

a.	Initiate collection measure to recover the aging and dormant account from persons liable and;

b.	Strictly abide with the provisions of Section 89 of PD No. 1445 particularly on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances by requiring the concerned officials and employees to submit immediately the complete supporting documents for the liquidation of cash advances and to avoid the grant of additional cash advance to officials and employees unless the previous cash advance is liquidated or a proper accounting thereof is made.
